deck_description: Yugi's Duelist Kingdom Deck is an EARTH/DARK Normal Monster Deck, which he received from his grandfather. Most of his Normal Monsters have low ATK, but he supports them with Spell Cards such as "Horn of the Unicorn" to raise their strength, while also maximizing his more powerful monsters' potential. If put on the defensive, he uses "Swords of Revealing Light" and "Magical Hats" to buy time for a comeback, or "Mirror Force" and "Spellbinding Circle" for a surprise counterattack. He also includes a bit of support for his signature card, "Dark Magician", like "Mystic Box". If all else fails, he resorts to Summoning mighty Ritual Monsters including "Black Luster Soldier" and "Magician of Black Chaos" for a reversal finish.

• Why no Astral Kuriboh? - You are will be locked into number monsters, if you never get Kashtira Birth you will be stuck with a no material diablosis that your opponent won't be able to remove, meaning you won't be able to summon your Kashtiras. Besides that card is outdated and a relic of pre-support Kash.
  • Why no Arsenal Falcon + Wind barrier? - Its a floodgate that hurts the deck more than helps it, unlike floo your only ways to normal summon are under Kashtira Birth , and thats once per turn, unless you are looping unicorns which is suboptimal, besides this card just like the deck dies to DRNM, any other board breaker or just the prevalent Floowander matchup. "Your scientists were so preoccupied with whether they could, they didn't stop to think if they should.”
  • Solemn Judgment - Solemn stops the pesky boardbreakers, Scareclaw Kash outs towers which the deck has problem dealing with, which is also why you run Underworld Goddess of the Closed World and Lava Golem . Also it should be noted that you should always start locking the backrow, it kills labrynth, Runciks, Stops Starter, Stops boardbreakers and then arise-heart should be able to deal with the Tears and the floo combo by banishing their cards.
  • Aussa the Earth Charmer, Immovable , Wynn the Wind Charmer, Verdant - Steals Fenrir and Unicorn from the GY

deck_name: Danger Dark World COMBO build for maximum consistency
deck_excerpt: 2nd place at locals, optimized for huge combos and consistency.
deck_description:
Hello fellow duelists.

I have been testing out Danger Darkworld ever since the structure deck dropped, and I am pleased to say it is one of my favorite combo decks of the current format. If you like gambling, ripping cards from your opponents hand, decks that require skill to play optimally and insane end boards then this deck might be the one for you. 

Some quick tips:

- Always go first

- Turbo Dugares and Coach King Giantrainer, protect them with an early Grapha fusion if possible

- If you are against Tear going second, scoop game one before they can mill you and get info on your deck, and go first in game 2, or else you're going to suffer the Abyss Dweller fate

- Do not activate the second effect of Mothman against Tearlament, ever

- Side in Neko Mane King going second against Tear, it's funny (trust me bro)

- Learn what is good Discard fodder and what is not (Genta, for example, is not, so you want it out of your hand immediately via activating its effect OR normal summoning it after its effect is used up)

- Search for archives with Snoww if you need extra draw power, fusion pieces if you want protection and hand loop pieces if you're already set up ("set up" meaning you've used Dugares, Coach King and Saryuja so you have 9+ cards in hand)

- Three easy side slots for going second are 2 Ceruli and 1 Sillva (because why try and hand loop if your opponent has no cards in hand?) The next three you can side out are 1 Mothman, 1 Grapha and 1 Accession

- Once you get faster with the deck, you can change Volcanic Scattershot with Infinite Impermanence in the side deck for better chances going second

- If your opponent is smart enough to play Droll & Lock Bird, side in the 1 Called by the Grave and pray

- Set your fusion spell after using it, it is a piece of your end board. If  your opponent uses Dark Ruler No More on you, you can use it to make your negate + hand loop live again (and if you have another Grapha in hand you even get a pop, so 2 interruptions PLUS a hand loop for two despite being DRNMd)

If you have any questions or want more help playing the deck, I am happy to be of service. I managed to come second place at my locals with this deck and lost out on first to Tearlament, so it should serve you well on a relatively low budget too if you take the time to learn it. Thanks for reading and/or looking at my deck profile.

deck_excerpt: Want to learn Domain Format? Check attached Youtube/Discord!
deck_description:
DOMAIN FORMAT
60 Main Deck
up to 15 extra deck
Any monster as your deckmaster (with balanced rules)
Deckmaster determines which Types/Attributes/Named Archetype monsters you can play
Nothing is banned
Singleton
Played in 4 player pods

My friends and I play Domain Format irl and in Discord. Others have compared it to the MTG Commander format. Anyone can come ask questions or learn the format to build a deck. https://discord.gg/GxXHC4qCYM

This is more than just slapping Invoked into a Deck that doesn't need its Normal Summon. For one, the Invoked package allows you to bait out interruptions and handtraps before you do your Prediction Princess plays. Secondly, Mechaba being a Level 9 monster allows you to get more advantage off of World Legacy Monstrosity than previously in this Deck since it allows you to practically search out Prediction Princess Bibliomuse which is such an integral card to your plays.

3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei and 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith. Tarotrei has a Quick Effect to flip a monster face-up or face-down and it can Summon a Flip monster from hand or GY during the End Phase. She facilitates Tarotreith who Summons a Flip monster from Deck face-down on flip and has a Quick Effect to flip any number of monsters you control face-up or face-down. 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. If there is a Flip monster you want the most in rotation in this Deck, this is the one. She adds a Prediction Princess monster and any Ritual Spell from your Deck on flip and she also provides targeting and destruction protection for your Ritual Monsters. But most importantly, she Summons herself back face-down after being Tributed which allows her to be flipped face-up by Tarotrei to be used as a searcher in your starting combo. 3 Aleister the Invoker. 2 Deus-X Krawler and 2 Pot of the Forbidden. We are playing 2 of each for Ritual fodder and as targets for World Legacy Monstrosity. Deus-X Krawler negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's field after being flipped and when it is destroyed (such as during the End Phase after being Summoned by World Legacy Monstrosity), it searches a Level 9 monster which is usually either Tarotrei or Tarotreith. Pot of the Forbidden is either Pot of Greed, Giant Trunade, Raigeki, or The Forceful Sentry on flip. It is good for removal or clearing boards and the drawing and shuffling back is good for building back advantage or preventing your opponent from gaining advantage. 3 Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands for extra searching for your Ritual-related cards. 1 Spirit of the Fall Wind as an extra searcher for your Flip Monsters. 

For Spell/Traps, we have 2 Invocation, 3 Pot of Prosperity, 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites, 1 Terraforming, 3 Magical Meltdown, 1 Called by the Grave. 3 World Legacy's Monstrosity which can Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and attribute than a Level 9 monster you control. In a more pure version of Prediction Princess, you would target Tarotrei to Summon Deus-X Krawler and Pot of the Forbidden to get Flip monsters into rotation and have material for a Rank 9. But because Bibliomuse is to important to your combo, you can do the Invoked line first to get an Invoked Mechaba under 5 Summons. This gives you a (monster) negate for handtraps like Nibiru or Ash which are killer against the Prediction Princess half of your Deck and because Mechaba is a Level 9 Light Machine, it gives you access to any 2 Level 9 monsters in your Deck off of World Legacy Monstrosity which includes Bibliomuse. This now gives you more access to Bibliomuse for your Prediction Princess plays more so than in a pure build of the Deck. Finally, we are playing 3 Prediction Ritual and 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction. We are only playing Prediction Ritual for the sake of making our Deck more consistent with Pre-Preparation of Rites.

Extra Deck: 2 Invoked Mechaba, 1 Invoked Purgatrio, 2 Herald of the Arc Light which is a target for Mereologic Aggregator. 2 Mereologic Aggregator which sends a monster from your Extra Deck to the GY, and more importantly, it can detach any number of materials to attach the same amount of monsters in your GY to it. This allows you to get the Flip monsters used for its Summon into the GY for Tarotrei. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. A unique kind of removal/disruption, but really good. 2 Phantom Fortress Enterblathnir if you want to start playing hand control later on into a game with Pot of the Forbidden. 2 Nine-Lives Cat which can reborn a Level 9 from your GY or a monster from your opponent's GY. And of course, the 1 Salamangreat Almiraj and 1 Secure Gardna for your Invoked plays.

Side Deck: 3 Kaijus, I am playing Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju since it is a Level 9 monster. 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being. 2 Spirit of the Fall Wind which you can side in if you want to go more heavy on the Prediction Princess side of your Deck. 3 Dark Ruler No More. 2 Cosmic Cyclone. And 3 Evenly Matched.

The Archfiend's Awakening (Erectti's Deck #14)

An Archfiend deck that contains overpowering support cards like the Pandemonium field to recharge your hand with more Archfiends, Falling Down spells to steal your opponent's monsters, Solidarity to boost all your fiends' attack power, and of course, the Dark Spirits of Malice & Banishment combined with Call of the Archfiends to make all your high-level fiends virtually UNKILLABLE! The modern age of the Archfiends is stronger than ever before!

Feedback is appreciated!

Do you like turning all your cards into Handtraps? Do you like German folk tales? Guns? Fps games? Generaider lore? Are your best friends called Smith & Wesson? Then boy do I have the deck for you! Load your Guns.

Main Deck:

Act 1: The Marksmen

All your Musketeer monsters share the effect: "During either player's turn, you can activate "Magical Musket" Spell/Trap Cards from your hand. If a Spell/Trap Card is activated in this card's column (except during the Damage Step)"

  • Magical Musketeer Caspar - Behold! Your searcher, you want to get him out as fast as possible with either Magical Musketeer Starfire or Magical Musketeer Max 
  • Magical Musketeer Starfire - Belle Starr over here can summon any of your musketeers from your deck, you want to summon Caspar first and then go into Doc or Kidbrave later on, thinning you deck so you only draw your Runick/Musket S/T.
  • Magical Musketeer Kidbrave - Billy the Kid can discard a dead musket card from your hand that you already used/wont be summoning to draw 2 cards, which can be used to draw your Runick/Musket S/T, and then you can recover those cards with Doc or Calamity.
  • Magical Musketeer Doc - Holyday over here recycles your dead musket cards from grave.
  • Magical Musketeer Calamity - Jane can reborns a dead musketeer in defense position, which means you can revive your Link monster.
  • Magical Musketeer Max - Max adds Musket S/T/summons Musketeers from Deck based on the number of monsters or S/T your opponent controls respectively. Max is more of an plan C in case your opponent finds a way to set-up under your disruptions.

Act 2: Arsenal

All Musket S/T can only be activated if you control a Musketeer monster.

  • Magical Musket - Cross-Domination - Negates and makes Atk/Def of the targeted monster to 0.
  • Magical Musket - Desperado - Pops a face-up card.
  • Magical Musket - Last Stand - S/T negate.
  • Magical Musket - Dancing Needle - Banishes 3 cards from GY.

These cards give the deck ways to deal with a lot of decks. Tears or Naturias causing trouble in the GY? Dancing needle. Pendulums or Runicks trying to do their stuff? Last Stand + Desperado. So you have a lot of options to choose from. Honorable mention to Called by the Grave and Super Polymerization which also help with the disruption game and triggering the musketeers.

Act 3: Deal with the Rune Devil

Like the Musketeers/Musket cards Runicks Quick-Plays can also be activated from hand if you control Runick Fountain making this an incredible combination, giving you an awful ammount of disruption with the cards from both decks while triggering the musketeer monsters.

  • Runick Fountain - As mentioned before, this card allows you to activate Runick Q-Ps from hand and if you do you can shuffle up to 3 Runick Spells from grave and then draw the same number of cards shuffled by this effect. Letting you draw more of your S/Ts
  • Runick Freezing Curses - Monster negate + Banish 3.
  • Runick Flashing Fire - Destroys a Special summoned monster + Banish 2.
  • Runick Destruction - S/T removal + Banish 4.
  • Runick Dispelling - Removes a card drawn by your opponent + Banish 2.
  • Runick Slumber - Protects a monster from being destroyed + Banish 3.
  • Runick Tip - Adds any Runick card + Banish 1.

Runicks as said before help in your disruption game and are you plan B in case you dont get any musketeer monsters, discarding the spells with Hugin the Runick Wings to fetch fountain.The more you cripple your opponent with the banish effects the better.

Extra: Tech Choices

  • Time-Rending Morganite - I don't like this one because its effect is not immediate but you have no monsters that activate in your hand.
  • Link into the VRAINS! - Helps bringing out Max without worrying about it being negated.
  • Ties of the Brethren - Free bodies but you would need to run more of the level 3s
  • Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries with Naturia Beast and Naturia Exterio - Naturias and SHS can access beast and Exterio is used by Springans and Vaylantz. They basically kill you if they ever get out so if you are sure about the match-up you can run some of these. Note Drnm or a Kaiju would be a better choice since the deck cant out towers.
  • Magical Musket - Crooked Crown and Magical Musket - Fiendish Deal - Zone lock which hurts U-links and decks reliant on columns like Vaylantz, Mekks and the dreaded Musketeer Mirror match. As for deal it protects you from decks that love to pop stuff. Problem with these 2 is that they lock your columns.

"Konami made Magical Musketeers and Konami made Magikeys, but Samuel Colt made them equal."

deck_excerpt: When it comes fresh, you know it's the best!
deck_description:
Hello There!

After getitng my butt beat at locals I decided to finally get bystials. Sadly the locals I go to does not have the remaining cards I need to complete the previous deck list. After doing some testing I ended up replacing 1 imperm and the 3 lubelion with 3 ghost ogre and 1 ernus. In testing the hards were still able to get to Sheou or Seal. 

Edit 1:

I was able to buy a Lubelion and an Imperm from my local card shop so I decided to drop Erunus and A Ghost Ogre from the main. Played against Live-Twins, Sprite (post ban list) and Despia. I went 1-3 which was a welcome improvement from the previous games. I might side out ghost ogre over dark ruler. Currently I am very happy with the deck!

Edit 2:

After playing locals this week, I decided to make a couple of adjustments. I went 2-2 tonight so an improvement overall. I lost against Swordsoul and Kashtira. The major changes are to the side deck, losing both Droll and the PSY gamma as Floo was not played as much anymore. Droll is still a good card to prevent special summons, but for right now I wanted to put a good front against Kashtira. I added Nib and Book of Eclipse, as well as an Appointer in order to get favorable going second matchups. Another change is removing Ghost Ogre entirely as currently it is not the best handtrap. I added the new Bystial but I might change that later as drawing a full hand of Bystials on going first is not the best. I am going to be looking into getting more draw potential with the deck. I will play around with using Kitchen Dragonmaid, as she can be a good card to save a dead hand. If your looking to build this deck or play it, let me know through comments!

deck_name: Firewall - Talker - Mathmech OTK Cyberstorm Access Support
deck_excerpt: Insane 1 Card OTK combo with lots of Negates.
deck_description:
Any ideas can be mentioned in the comments.

 

1 Card combo with Mathmech Circular

1. Special Summon "Mathmech Circular" from the Hand and throw "Mathmech Sigma" in GY - Use effect of "Mathmech Sigma to special summon itself"

Then use use effect of Circular to search "Mathmech Equation"

 

2. Use both Mathmech cards to XYZ summon "Primathmech Alembertian" - Use his effect to search "Mathmech Addition" or "Mathmech Subtraction"

-> Use second effect of Alermbertian to special summon Sigma from GY. Activate Addition or Subtraction to special summon them

 

3. Use one of those to Link summon "Salamangreat Balelynx", and search "Salamangreat Sanctuary". Now use the remaining Mathmech Monster and Balelynx to Link summon "Cyberse Witch"

 

4. Activate "Mathmech Equation" to special summon Alembertian to a zone Cyberse Witch points to -> Use effect to search "Cyberse Sage" and "Cynet Ritual". Then use second effect of Cyberse Witch to special summon 1 Monster from GY.

 

5. Activate "Cynet Ritual" and use one of your Monsters as Material (Either the one summoned by Equation or you have one in Hand). Use effect of the summoned "Cyberse Sage" to Fusion summon "Cyberse Disabwurm", using Balelynx and one other Monster from your GY as Materials.

 

6. Synchro summon "Cyberse Quantum Dragon" by using "Cyberse Sage" and "Cyberse Disabwurm" as Materials. Use effect of Sage in GY to return Circular to Hand.

 

7. Link summon "Transcode Talker" by using "Cyberse Witch" and "Primathmech Alembertian". Activate his effect to special summon Witch to a zone Transcode points to.

 

8. Use "Transcode Talker", "Cyberse Witch" and "Cyberse Quantum Dragon" to Link summon "Firewall Dragon Darkfluid" and activate his effect to gain 4 Counters

Ps: If possible, use cards like "Parallel eXceed", "Firewall Defenser" -> "Firewall Guardian" or "Firewall Phantom" to special summon "Protectcode Talker". Also try to search "Gatchiri @Ignister", and use him for a Link summon, then activate his effect to protect Darkfluid until the end of the opponents turn. Cards to search are: "Cynet Mining" and "Cynet Codec" (Searchable when you use Micro Coder from your Hand as a Link Material). If you go for "Cynet Codec" make sure to summon "Transcode Talker" afterwards, so you can search the Earth-type Monster, Gatchiri. Also you can use "Micro Coder" to search the Omni-Negate "Cynet Conflict". If you use "Code Generator from your hand as a Link Material, use his effect to send "Dotscaper" from your Deck to GY to special summon itself.

deck_description: It is actually Insane that a strictly Insect Deck has enough support to focus so well on level modulation and XYZ evolution.

Frightfur is a fun an interesting decks with nonlinear combos and scythe (no not that one) providing the ability to fusion summon on your openents turn for some cool interaction. This deck is also suprisingly good at procking scythe (yes that one). While I haven't included it in this list, you can simply swap out a hand trap or a copy of fluffal wings for a scythe and then any extra deck monster for dagda. The nature of toy vendor, wings, and penguin also provide for some very funny moments where you draw or mill exactly what you need. End boards vary a lot with you often bringing out a toad and a 3-4 material apollousa. A scythe in hand can then be used to summon out a whale for a non taget pop, or a tiger for a 2+ targeted pop.Sacred tree beast, Hyperyton is simply here as a negate if you manage to bring out 2 crule whales on your turn (it happens more often than you'd think). Finally eldlich is here as it is one of the best cards to discard off of toy vendor and then you can use it's effect to send the toy vendor to grave getting a free 3500 body on field and a search from the toy vendor in grave.

deck_excerpt: Mystic Mine is banned in Masterduel - so the "Five-Rainbow Lock" is the next best thing!
deck_description:
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!


Mystic Mine is banned in Masterduel - so the "Five-Rainbow Lock" is the next best thing!

The pendulum effect of Five-Rainbow Magician is as follows: You cannot Pendulum Summon, except from the Extra Deck. This effect cannot be negated.

Each player applies 1 of these effects based on the number of Set cards in their Spell & Trap Zones.

● 0: All monsters they control cannot attack or activate their effects.

● 4 or more: The ATK of all monsters they control become double their original ATK.

Lock your opponent out of effects/attacks by not letting them set any cards! If they set a card in the backrow, pop them with Paleozoic Olenoides, Dogmatika Punishment or Heavy Storm Duster!

In the meantime, beatdown your opponent with your gigantic monsters with DOUBLE attack! (For example, 3000 ATK Ecclessia >:3)

If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!

Have fun trolling Duelists! :trollface:

deck_excerpt: A working abomination of a budget deck
deck_description: For all the people pretending to understand the meta
Rank 4 XYZ

Deck dies pretty much instantly if you have NO WAY to obtain cynet codec or you get ash blossom'd on search.

Cynet Codec is your win condition and if used well can create a U-Link

You need to play it from your hand as soon as possible.

You can get it using Micro Coder, Lady Debug (by searching Micro Coder) or Cynet mining to get Lady debug.

Then you kinda just spam link monsters?

Code talker -> Code Talker Inverted -> Transcode Talker (summon back Code talker inverted) -> Go into excode talker using inverted + a new monster -> Accescode using excode + new monster -> Get out update jammer with more monsters -> use update jammer + new monster to go into heatsoul -> draw 1 of heatsoul -> summon a cyberse monster go into Linguriboh.

There you go U-link (this can be done easily if you use Cynet Codec well)

More in depth explanation will be coming soon.

deck_description:
I was building a deck for my little sister to play, and two cards I never even knew I had caught my eye: "Melffy Pony", and "Melffy Fenny". Just looking at the card art, I knew she would love them. So I put them both in the deck, despite the fact that the Melffy and Performapals don't really mesh well.

And I was right. She absolutely adored them. Curious, I looked on the internet to see if there were more cards, and sure enough, there was. I was flooded by card art that looked like it had been designed by a furry off of twitter. So I built this deck as sort of a representation of her.

I also just realized this is once again my newest most expensive deck so far! Boy do I love decimating the population of currency within my wallet!

If you guys have any recommendations, or just remember that your comments are always welcome here. :)

deck_excerpt: A cheap deck for competitive Yu-Gi-Oh! (Cheaper or more expensive options available.)
deck_description:
This is a deck I made so that I could play at a competive level at Yu-Gi-Oh!

Cheaper card options.

Cynet Mining: There is no other cheap way to easily search out cards, as the other option would be: Small World, but the card is much more complicated, expensve, and works worse than Cynet Mining. So maybe just add some cheap generic cards because the deck is consistant enough already.

Expensive options:

Ghost Ogre: Either: Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, or: Infinite Impermanence, or: Effect Veiler.

Effect Veiler: Either: Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, or: Infinite Impermanence.

You can add 1 Mathmech Sigma, but the card is a brick, and most of the time not that usefull.

You could also add: small world for an extra search, for the price for two banished cards, -1, and your brain power.

this deck builds off exploting the flexibility of cynet mining to find either fire or paladin of storm dragon

The mainline combo is to get first apperance, fire, agent on field and doombroker in hand

link off fire for linkuriboh, agent effect bring fire back, normal fire, link fire plus linkuriboh for cyberse witch

ritual doombroker to witch zone and use witch's ablility (assuming you use at least one spell to hand fix, also why the sparks are in the list just as activatable spells, they can be replaced by upstarts if you have them, but sparks is funnier)

witch adds a cynet ritual and paladin of storm dragon, and then activates again to resummon (for the third time) our fire

cynet ritual summons paladin, paladin tributes self for code exporter, code exporter on field plus the witch makes heatsoul, triggering code exporter to summon back another 4 (paladin, fire, doesn't matter much)

you then have a couple of lines depending on how many extra materials you have, if you had two paladins in hand from hand fixing earlier you have an extra body, if you had access to geek boy you have an extra body, with two bodies you can make i:p and threaten unicorn with heatsoul and/or apollusa with the monster summoned after negating with intervention. If you have two 4s you can make a rank 4, i only have redoer in this list but you could flex any rank 4 you want including bagooska but it would negate any monster you summon off of intervention. with two extra bodies you can even 

regardless you end on heatsoul and doombroker (find intervention)

turn three while you also have access to the libro mainline engine, you also have access to the very rarely read graveyard effect of cynet ritual, which reads if you have an empty board banish this and a ritual monster to summon 2 level 4 tokens, which both gives you link material and a body on field to reset doombroker's direct attack effect.

note, all of the hand traps are mostly crossout targets and can be replaced with any flex slots you want

deck_name: The Most Playable Tindangle Deck Ever
deck_excerpt: What the heck are the Penguins doing here?
deck_description:
Behold. An almost playable Tindangle deck that doesn't floodgate your opponent into oblivion (but can side into that). 

Wait did I say doesn't floodgate, I mean doesn't use unbased floodgates, but rather based floodgates instead. 

Here is your win condition number 1: Tindangle Acute Cerberus. It's a terrible card, but trust me if the stars line up, its a 3k monster that can be equipped with Gergonne's End and therefore become untargettable and indestructible. Also if you use Dholes to summon it, it can attack 3 times :D.

How likely is this to come up? 

Well you don't see Nagel's Protection doubling battle damage in this deck, so I think you can assume this is not going to happen very often. And I have no clue how to make it happen often without more support or floodgating your opponent until they're a geriatric from how long they are sitting in the chair you have forced them into. At least without some new Tindangle support. 

So I'm sure you're asking now. Now what? The main boss don't appear often and you can't make the great wall of indestructible DEF position monsters Nagel's Protection can create for funsies. 

Well.. uhh....

If you can't Link your way to victory, then how about HEROES? I mean all of these are Dark Monsters, Dholes, Delaunuy and Toddler like being discarded... so throw in Mask Change 2, and you have DARK LAW...

which is a start i suppose...

Put hear this! If you draw Penguin Squire and a Level 6, 5 or 3, which if you haven't noticed are a bit abundant in this deck, you can make a SYNCHRO PLAY!!!

WHAT? SYNCHROS IN MY LINK DECK? 

Well... Yeah, Penguin Brave is a 6 that lets you set Penguin Soldier from deck, and gives you a 2 Bounce Interupption, that also happens to protect your face-down monsters passively, while the Level 10 Icejade Synchro is just big, and does things... i think...

Uh... 

HEY WHAT ABOUT XYZ's?? Crimson Ninja is a 5 that will always survive a regular battle, so you can turn it into Zeus. But wait a second! If your opponent happens to have a monster with less than 2000 attack, Doom Chimera Dragon can get itself AN EXTRA MATERIAL, SO WHEN IT BECOMES ZEUS, YOU GET 2 ACTIVATIONS. 

DEAR LORD THE POWER!!!

...

Yeah, there's no other way to hype this deck up, but I'm sure it can win against something in a based way... though honestly dude, I think you're better off just adding in floodgates and Nagel's Protection and just making the Imperial Wall of indestructible idiots than whatever this is.

Rescue Ace (Feb 2023)

My own take on the Danger-Gren Maju deck. Overall strategy is still the same: Pot of Desires and Gizmek Orochi to banish as many cards as you can to power up Gren Maju Da Eiza in order to win by brute force. Only Danger! monsters are the Level 8 and Level 3 versions. The Level 8 ones make it extremely easy to XYZ summon one of the strong XYZ monsters, while Links are used for support with the high number of Special Summons that Gizmek and Danger!s can perform. Plenty of hand traps, making it a more defensive Gren Maju deck, giving you opportunity to stall/block an opponent's setup while working on banishing. Spells are split between trading out resources and blocking opposing plays to increase the amount of time you have to set up Gren Maju. Fusions are easy to summon with Super Poly, and Links are mostly there for extra support. Winged Dragon? Honestly, that's just a surprise pick if you decide to run Sphere Mode.

deck_excerpt: Pure, Ninja, Ninjitsu, OTK, Control, Advantage
deck_description:
It's Ninja Time! After many years Ninja finally seem to have a competent Strategy true to their name and I will analyze that today. So let's go more into Detail and see what makes the Archnemesis of the Six Samurai so special: 

 

Entering the World Shrouded in Darkness

Like with every Deck you need Starters to get things going. Thankfully Ninjas have a big selection to choose from and bricking is a very rare occurrence. The Ninja Grandmaster Hanzo has to be the best Starter for them to this day. He will search anything you desire to get into bigger Control setups. Just beware since both of his effects will miss Timing if summoned mid Chain. But since he has no Once per Turn feel free to loop his Ninja Monster search many times. For example tribute Jioh the Gravity Ninja with Ninjitsu Art of Duplication to special 2 Hanzo's from Deck and search any 2 Ninja Monsters to your hand.

The Ninjitsu Art Notebook is very nice to search for any other Ninjitsu art and setup the GY. It's even better if you recycle this card back to your Hand with Baku the Beast Ninja and/or Ninjitsu Art of Dancing Leaves since the Notebook is missing a Hard Once Per Turn. Feel free to use it up to 3 Times in one Turn if the Heart of the Cards is on your side. With this Card alone it's easy to setup every necessary Ninjitsu that you want as early as turn one.

Cards like Mitsu the Insect Ninja , Green Ninja , Yellow Ninja, Tobari the Sky Ninja , Kagero the Cannon Ninja , Upstart Golden Ninja  and the Quick Play Ninjitsu Art Notebook of Mystery all help to get your Deck up to speed. There's a big Selection to choose from and many Combos to be found here. So in total getting your Deck up to speed is easy. Fast and swift like Ninjas you could say.

 

Defending the Village from Intruders

Keeping the opponent at Bay/Removing Threats is your Number One Priority before getting agressive yourself. The newer Ninjas all have on theme in Common: Flipping Monsters Face Up and Face Down always and everywhere. 

Mitsu the Insect Ninja is a great Example to Start with. She can Flip up a Face Down Monster on your side to negate a Monster Effect activated by the opponent and Flip herself down again. Tobari the Sky Ninja enables Quick Effect Fusion Summons. Like that you can summon either Meizen the Battle Ninja for more Ninja Swarming during the opponents turn or the new Threat on the Horizon Yaguramaru the Armor Ninja. He can on summon target and Banish a Card from the field and if you Flip him down and later Face Up again this effect may be reused multiple Times over many turns. Also he's setting up your banished pile for Ninjitsu Art Tool - Iron Digger.

Another Formidable Choice is to summon Jioh the Gravity Ninja to set up to 2 Monsters from the opponent or yourself Face Down. In Addition the opponents monsters cannot change their Battle Position even if Jio gets Removed from the field. Meizen the Battle Ninja can summon Jio very easily from Deck if the opponent activates any Card or Effect. Jio also has a nice Removal build in if something gets flipped, so he's just good all around. 

There's many more defensive Tools too. You can Halve the ATK of every Special summoned Monster with Armor Ninjitsu Art of Rust Mist, Protect yourself from Attacks, Destruction or Targeting through various means with cards like Meizen the Battle Ninja , Ninja Grandmaster Saizo or Hidden Village of Ninjitsu Arts or Replace Monsters on the field with Kagero the Cannon Ninja. Or destroy your own Ninjitsu Art Notebook of Mystery with Jio for example to get a Flip Down for any Monster on the field. The same can be achieved if you use Green Ninja as Fusion Material during the opponents turn. It's not an easy task to bring down this defensive Style of Gameplay with usual OTK Strategies. The Ninjas move fast within the Shadows and duplicate rapidly.

 

The unexpected Sneak Attack from Behind

Your Main Victory Condition will be Meizen the Battle Ninja. He enables every Ninja to attack directly. An easy Combination would be summoning him equipped with Ninjitsu Art Tool - Iron Digger and XYZ summon Blade Armor Ninja on top of that. With these 2 on field you create a Meizen which attacks twice directly with 3000 ATK and Blade Armor Ninja with his 2200 ATK is the final touch to deal 8200 total Damage through Direct attacks. Since every Ninja can attack directly feel free to Combine this effect in many ways. Your Biggest possible Ninja is Meizen the Battle Ninja equipped with 3 Iron Digger's and Ferocious Flame Swordsman on the field, making him 4500 ATK Strong. 

Senior Silver Ninja should get a short mention here too. When he's flipped up you can special any Number of any Ninja Monsters you like from Hand and/or the GY in Face Down defense Position. Very useful to set up tons of different plays and confuse the opponent. This Card will catch the opponents attention almost always.

That's all for this Section.

But there's a very tiny little hidden tool left to uncover.... 

 

The Mosquito Strikes Back!

Number 2: Ninja Shadow Mosquito is your secret Weapon in this Deck. This Card can't be destroyed by Battle and you receive no Battle Damage from it. In addition it forces every Monster to attack you if possible. If an Attack is declared from the opponent or from you, you can place a Hallucination Counter on one of the opponents Monsters. This will negate any effects that Monster has. 

With that explained here's the win Condition: Mosquito can activate it's 2nd effect to Deal Damage to the opponent equal to the ATK of one Monster with a Hallucination Counter whenever a attack is declared from any Player. Every strong OTK Board will fall into this Tricky Monsters trap resulting in easy reverse OTK wins. It's a truly fascinating card. A very tiny yet very dangerous little Mosquito.

 

The Big Ninjitsu Trick Box

By this Point you might be wondering why I play 3 Copies of Ninjitsu Art Tool - Iron Digger and also 3 Copies of Ninjitsu Art of Dancing Leaves. These 2 cards combo very strongly with each other. Use Iron Digger to equip it to an opponents Monster making it a Ninja Monster and then use Iron Digger's 2nd effect to destroy 1 Card on the field by banishing one Ninja from the GY. Then activate Dancing Leaves to Tribute the opponents "Ninja" Monster and Special any 1 other Ninja Monster from Deck, also triggering Iron Diggers 3rd effect to recycle the earlier Banished monster to the Hand or Special it Face Down to the field. If you add Baku the Beast Ninja to the Mix he will be able to Recycle the Iron Digger too making it essencially an infinite Advantage Combo.

Just imagine all the Advantage: Removing 2 Cards from the opponent, Special one Ninja from Deck, Add one Ninja from the Banished Zone back to Hand, Recycle Iron Digger back to Hand and Dancing Leaves with it's own effect potentially too and Loop this every Turn. Amazing stuff right there. 

And that's not all. Other Ninjitsu Arts and little interactions between each Ninja make this Deck very versatile in it's usage. Green Ninja for example helps a huge amount in setting and flipping Monsters anywhere on the field or use Ninjitsu Art of Mirage-Transformation to steal a Monster from the opponents GY and treat it as "Ninja" Monster. Or destroy your own Ninjitsu Art Notebook of Mystery to get a free Book of Moon.

Also I didn't even mention the fact they have 2 Field Spells. Tenchi Kaimei can Destroy 1 Card whenever Damage is inflicted to the opponent and should the opponent remove it it's basically Senior Silver Ninja as punishment for doing so. Hidden Village of Ninjitsu Arts can recycle 100% everything Ninja or Ninjitsu related back to the Hand when a Ninja is summoned during either player's turn. It prevents using the effects of that card for the rest of the Turn as minor downside. Also it can protect every card from Destruction by Banishing a Ninja from the GY instead, once again setting up Iron Digger. Thanks to Cards like Baku you can easily Change between the 2 Field Spells at will, whatever suits the Situation.

Having a Draw 2 Spell with Armor Ninjitsu Art of Alchemy is useful too. It's especially good if you have only Notebook active since in Order to Draw 2, you have to destroy all Ninjitsu Cards under your Control. How convenient then that Notebook can search for it and Hidden Village or Baku can recycle it.

Number 12: Crimson Shadow Armor Ninja looks like another Strange inclusion but look closer. 2 Copies of Yaguramaru the Armor Ninja can create him and enable Quick effect Destruction protection for all Ninja Monsters while further setting up your GY. He comes up more often then you might think. 

Ninja Grandmaster Saizo is a 2k Dude which can protect himself from Attacks and Targeting effects. But the better part about him is that he can set a Ninjitsu Art Card every turn directly from the Deck. He's useful for sure. Also he and the Notebook Spells can't be stopped through cards like Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. Saizo can't even be stopped through Infinite Impermanence thanks to targeting protection. Amazing! 

Lastly there's Ferocious Flame Swordsman in the ED. He's nice to strengthen the Meizen OTK and very interesting to run into an opponents Monster to Special one additional Ninja to make the OTK even easier. 

So in total everything in the Main Deck is either a Ninja or a Ninjitsu Art in perfect 20/20 balance, and they can be recycled easily many times not only but mostly with the Field Spell or the Ninjitsu Art Notebook of Mystery The Ninja Gas is truly endless.

 

Six Samurai burn the Village down

So Ninja is the best Deck ever right? Yeah no.... Like almost every Deck it Struggles against certain Floodgates and to much Negation on Board. Also having no access to Mass Removal/non targeting removal outside of the big Bomb Five-Headed Link Dragon can turn out to be a Problem. The reliance on Ninjitsu Cards can make a Lightning Storm very devastating too. Be aware of some of the usual offenders when you choose to play this Deck. 

As for the more specific weaknesses: If a Ninjitsu Art gets banished through cards like Macro Cosmos it's gone for good. Only Ninja Monsters can return from the Banished Zone through Iron Digger or in more desperate Situations Bujinki Amaterasu.

Having Hanzo able to Miss Timing is unfortunate since you can't use Meizen to summon him Face Up Mid Chain (You can however set him). The Hidden Village can recycle cards like Baku but sadly he cannot use his effect then. Minor Archetype issues but issues nontheless. 

Then again Mosquito and Meizen can really turn the tables quite often so do your best to keep them around. This kind of Ninja Strategy is very unknown and can easily surprise the opponent. 

 

Extinguishing the Fire and saving the Village

Ninjas exist since the dawn of Yugioh (27.05.1999 OCG Armed Ninja), but only now over 20 Years Later they became a well rounded Strategy. Since they use the Face Down Defense Position a lot they can play around quite a bit of Removal, Negation and Floodgate effects. It's up to the player to decide which Tool to use and when's the right moment to do so. Having access to so many different Combo lines within one Deck is truly fascinating. 

If you decide to pick Ninjas up, expect a Control oriented Strategy which can achieve easy OTKs and has a lot of Tools at their disposal. In addition you will notice how almost every card in the Archetype will generate Card Advantage which makes this Strategy an endless Pool of Ressources. In short: They are a lot of fun and never get boring. 

 

Final Rating: 

★★★★★★ OTK Potential

★★★★☆☆ Defensive Tools

★★★★★☆ Control Options

★★★☆☆☆ Removal Options

★★★★★★ Recovery/Recycling

★★★★★★ Card Advantage

Overall Rating: ★★★★★★

 

 

Ninjas Break all the Rules

I will list some not so obvious rulings down below: 

Jioh the Gravity Ninja: 1.Opponents monsters that are flipped face down through his effect remain face down and cannot change their position even if Jio leaves the field. 

Senior Silver Ninja: 1.His effect can miss timing if he is flipped up mid Chain/on an not open Gamestate. 2.He has no Once per Turn Limitation. 3.Since he summons multiple Ninja Monsters you have to show all Ninja Monsters you want to summon first BUT you don't have to show in which Zone you summon them face down after. 

Upstart Golden Ninja: 1.Using his or similar effects always forces you to show the Monster to the opponent to Confirm that it's a Ninja Monster. The same applies for Cards which set Ninjitsu Arts from Deck. 

Ninja Grandmaster Hanzo: 1.Both of his Effects can miss Timing. If you summon him mid Chain/on an not open Gamestate he cannot use his effect. 2.He has no Once Per Turn Limitations on his effects. 

Armor Ninjitsu Art of Alchemy: 1.This Card has no Once Per Turn Limitation and can be used multiple times in one turn.

Tenchi Kaimei: 1.Both effects on this Card have no Once Per Turn and there's no activation Limitation on this card.

Hidden Village of Ninjitsu Arts: 1.The effect which recycles one Card back to your Hand only prevents you from activating it or the effects for the rest of the turn. A Ninja Monster can still be Normal Summoned/Set and use it's effect on the following turn normally. 

Ninjitsu Art Tool - Iron Digger: 1.You can equip this Card to any Monster on both sides of the field. Like this you can treat an opponents Monster as a Ninja Monster. 

Ninjitsu Art Notebook of Mystery: 1.Since this card is a quick effect you can chain it during your first turn when the opponent activates cards such as Infinite Impermanence. 2.You can choose whether you want to set 1 or 2 Cards and from which place Deck and/or GY freely. 3.Popular cards like Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring  cannot be used to stop this search. It sets directly from Deck just like the original Ninjitsu Art Notebook and Ninja Grandmaster Saizo too. 

Armor Ninjitsu Art of Rust Mist: 1.The halfed ATK remain even if this Card leaves the field. 2.If at resolution there's no Ninja on the field anymore you still half the ATK of the opponents Monster. 

Ninjitsu Art of Mirage-Transformation: 1.This Card and similar Cards who need to Tribute a Ninja as cost in Order to activate can also choose a Face Down Ninja Monster as Tribute. 

Ninjitsu Art of Duplication: 1.This Card has no Once Per Turn Limitations and can be used multiple times. 2.If you return this Card to the Hand with Baku the Beast Ninja and chain the quick effect of Tobari the Sky Ninja  to it you can both summon a Fusion Monster with Baku and Tobari as Material, and get Duplication back to the Hand. 

Ninjitsu Art of Dancing Leaves: 1.This Card can Tribute a monster from anywhere on the field, the opponents field included. 2. This Card can return itself back to the Hand too. 

Meizen the Battle Ninja: 1.You can use Face Down Monsters as Material to fulfill this Cards summoning Condition. Tobari the Sky Ninja can also use Face Down Monsters as Fusion Material for his effect and the same applies to Yaguramaru the Armor Ninja.

Blade Armor Ninja: 1.After using his effect successfully the ability to attack Twice this turn cannot be negated anymore through cards like Skill Drain.

Number 2: Ninja Shadow Mosquito: 1.This Card has no Once Per Turn Limitations. 2.The effect which places Hallucination Counters does not target and can be used on Normal Monsters too. 3.A defense Position Monster is not forced to Switch to Attack Position or to attack at all. Only Attack Position Monsters have to attack.

deck_excerpt: Meta-ish, but not quite, Vampire Deck
deck_description:
This is the deck as I have it now. There are definitely more upgrades to be made but money is delaying that process. The deck performs well but likely could only compete against other decks that aren't quite meta-level but contain some meta-level cards. It might perform well in a small local tournament or something but it depends. It's very combo-heavy and a hand trap or interruption can really ruin your turn, especially if timed well.

Regardless, this deck is a lot of fun and one of my favorite decks that I've played with -- partially because I think vampires are cool and partially because it's actually a fun playstyle. When playing casually with friends, I take out the hand traps (a "house-rule" amongst us) and it still performs well, typically winning more than it loses.

Ojama black wandered through the forest at night, a lost soul, damaged, forgotten, useless. "Why have things turned out this way?" He thought. He was so sad and lonely. Ojama yellow had left him and ran off with Ojama green, they had started a new life together without him, leaving him with nothing but the trees and his budgy smugglers. The last he heard they had a house and some kids and ran around in striped pajamas all day. He clenched his fist and stared at the ground "Why was I not enough?" He said. He continued his walk along a long winding path that led to nowhere, sneezing out another snot bubble. He was finding a secure branch that would support his weight when suddenly, a bright light appeared in front of him and a figure came forth to stand there. A beautiful woman? No, not a woman...an ANGEL, he gasped.... She leaned in toward him and calmly took the rope from his hands. "The world is in great peril, Ojama black. As we speak duelists are flooding the edge of our forest. They mean to cause us harm". Ojama black was confused. He had only ever seen a duelist once and they sent him to the graveyard. "What does this have to do with me?" He asked. He sounded quite selfish. Her face darkened and her third eye glared into his soul. "You need to understand. Your life will be no more if the duelists take over. You, Ojama yellow and Ojama green along with all the other monsters of the forest" she said. He stared blankly at her, then the realization slowly started to set in. Ojama blacks palms became sweaty and his mouth felt dry. "Ojama yellow will be no more?" He choked. Tears started at the edges of his eyes and he could feel himself shaking, then, after a brief moment his expression changed. He looked serious and turned to face the figure in front of him "What do I need to do?". She lifted one majestic arm and gestured to the trees. "We are harnessing the power of great beings, the likes of which you have never seen, by combining our strength in fusion. Without you and your fellow Ojama's our hope of success is non-existent. Find your family, Ojama black. Find them and come to me." She lowered her arm and turned away before Ojama black could respond. Then another bright light flashed and she was gone. Ojama black stood for a moment and stared at the place the angel had been standing. A moment ago he was ready to end it all but now he felt different. "I must save them!" He said loudly to the forest and with that he picked up some moss and shoved it up his nose to staunch the endless flow of liquid. Then he set off in one direction to find his family and begin the fight for his people. The end.

deck_excerpt: A little known deck but with excellent synergies and a lot of variety of moves
deck_description:
The main reason behind this combination of engines is not to lose to an interaction going first or second with the Dinosaur engine which is very strong when it comes out of inertia but with several weak points for that to happen.

This deck I put together the first version when Chaos Ruler, the Chaotic Magical Dragon was still in the game and the existing synergies really work. And here the Miscellaneousaurus limitation does not become a lock for you to make excellent plays while you have follow up.

 

Improvements this deck has for an exclusive Dinosaur engine:

1 - Many combinations of starting hands that have more than one move, that is, you don't depend on resolving an effect to be able to play like your normal summon or Miscellaneosaurus.

2 - Recovery of moves much higher than before, Dinosaur cards are not very good at generating follow up to redo the field again without having access to Miscellaneousaurus or some way to destroy a Babycerasaurus. Now you have the Ogdoadic which itself always cycles every turn and also Aleirtt, the Ogdoadic Dark returns Miscellaneousaurus to the GY.

3 - More ways to break the field with the engine of Scrap Raptor and Ogdoadic. Now there are many powerful cards that you can access in different ways like Evilswarm Exciton Knight, Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star and Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder.

4 - The Extra deck continues to follow the pattern of cards that work well for the Dinosaur deck, such as LINK-2 and XYZ RANK-4 monsters, but with many more ways to access them and enhance the combos.

5 - There are so many details in this version of the deck that compared to the basic version of a Dinosaur deck here you discover moves every new game, it is a very creative deck.

 

////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////Now the best thing is to learn in practice:

I work with reality because you need to make safer game development where you analyze Risk vs Reward. I don't do combos that are pretty to look at but that in practice lose to hand traps or are too exaggerated with a lot of negates that you don't need like the ones they use (Apollousa + Borreload Savage + Evolzar Lambda):

 

- The Dinosaur engine has always had a play theme around the Babycerasaurus card with many combinations of standard 2 card combos landing on the same end board;

- The Scrap Raptor engine amplifies what is already good in the deck's basic plays to access the Extra Deck with more game volume.

- These are the basic combos involving only these Dinosaur Scrap engines;

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46457912

Archosaur + Babycerasaurus or Petiteranodon

 

(remember Archosaur + Baby = Oviraptor + Babycerasaurus = Miscellaneousaurus + Baby = Oviraptor + Miscellaneousaurus - just have a little details in the start but the end board is the same)

Tyranno + Dolkka + Omega + Spright Elf + Petiteranodon

In any of these combos you will get the following cards: Oviraptor + Baby + Scrap Raptor + Archosaur (or Linkuriboh in the case of the Archosaur + Baby combo) + Double Evolution Pill in the Hand

or

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46458231

The difference here is that you don't play around hand trap doing Evolzar Dolkka early, but do it only in the middle of the combo and that way you end up having one more monster on the field which means being able to do one more XYZ like Abyss Dweller. A risky but very strong move.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46458427

Lost World + Oviraptor

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46458731

Lost World + Scrap Raptor

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46458957

Scrap Raptor + Miscellaneosaurus

 

These were just examples of what the Dinosaur Scrap engine is capable of doing on its own. Now let's apply the Ogdoadic engine as well.

Here you can choose to play safe and make King of the Feral Imps to add Nauya to your hand because he is the best starter of the Ogdoadic engine.

Finally, on the gameplay of why the deck is interesting: Turn 1 you usually spend with what Dinosaur Scrap does best which is Tyranno + Evolzar Dolkka + Spright Elf and what Ogdoadic does best which is a XYZ RANK-8.

What makes this deck oppressor are the follow ups, on the next turn you have the you can have (Chaos Ruler in the GY - se a carta sair da banlist LOL) that along with the Ogdoadic engine threatens Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star, you also easily threaten to do Exciton Knight, there's Miscellaneousaurus + Giant Rex that threaten Tyranno / Pankratops + XYZ RANK-4 which is giant in the grind game. 

So you generate so much advantage in GY that it's no use your opponent breaking your field, he'll have to OTK because otherwise your turn is scary. This is not the new secret deck that destroys the meta but I believe it is the best way to still play Dino besides being fun and requiring considerable skill because it is not linear, each combo I present can be done differently depending on from gamestate, there are times when you can connect de uma forma que você nunca pensou antes.

 

COMBOS INVOLVING CHAOS RULER AND BORRELOAD SAVAGE (when I used the card):

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46459669

Miscellaneousaurus + Babycerasaurus

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33376148

This combo was not done in a didactic way but it already shows the potential of the deck's moves.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33380488

Snake Rain + Discard + Scrap Raptor = I:P Masquerena + Bagooska /in GY: Chaos Ruler + all the Ogdoadic names /in Hand: Search of Chaos Ruler

(The first time I had summoned from Aron because of the autopilot but you must summon from Nauya to access Bagooska)

 

COMPLETE ENGINE BASIC COMBO:

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46459967

END BOARD: Tyranno + Dolkka + Spright Elf + Petiteranodon + Number 38

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33348273

Basic Combo version showing that you can easily play with just 1 Scrap Raptor, you don't need to use the second copy to make the combo.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33373914

In this combo, you just need to transform the Scrap Wyvern + Linkuriboh at the end into the Spright Elf and the result will be the same.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33374185

This version of the Combo I made just to demonstrate the synergy that exists between Tyranno + Scrap Wyvern when he destroys the Scrap Chimera by using its effect:

Ultimate Conductor Tyranno is not just Book of Eclipse but a pop without targeting additionally because you destroy Scrap Chimera and Scrap Wyvern's eff trigger to give summon from Scrap Raptor that we still have in the deck to pop a card without targeting, that way you don' t need to use Tyranno's effect so early in the combo)

This is just so you can see that there is this synergy between these cards on the end board, but of course the most efficient thing is to transform the Wyvern + Chimera into the Spright Elf, which makes practically the same point of bringing Pankratopos in this case to destroy cards on the field, but here Pankratops is more efficient since you don't need to use the pop effect as soon as you use Tyranno's effect, here you can wait but this possibility is very important thing to remember between Tyranno + Scrap Wyvern.

 

INDIVIDUAL PLAYS DURING THE GAME IMPORTANT TO SEE:

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46460512

BLIND SECOND PLAY: Oviraptor + Miscellaneosaurus

(It's not hard to make Exciton Knight with the Ogdoadic engine too)

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-34766275

Let's assume a grind game situation that happens with Lost World + Oviraptor

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33374781

Lost World + Babycerasaurus Blind Second = FULL COMBO

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33337033

Archosaur + Giant Rex (any Dino Lv4) = RANK-8

This combo is good to remember the detail that Archosaur can add Nauya or Nunu to the hand when destroying a Level 4 Dinosaur which means that in cases where you already have a Double Evolution Pill in your hand you can make this move to access the Ogdoadic engine without needing the King of the Feral Imp. This is important to remember in hands that don't come as strong to increase the number of possible moves.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33364312

Oviraptor + Double Evolution Pill = Tyranno + RANK-8 (Number 38) /in GY: Miscellaneousaurus + 4 Ogdoadic names

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33379559

Oviraptor + Babycerasaurus + Nunu

This combo is good for you to see that when you want to avoid losing right away in the normal summon you can first Special Summon Nunu so in case of interaction you can do King of the Feral Imps and still have moves to do on the turn.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46461244

Scrap Raptor + Miscellaneousaurus = Version with the Ogdoadic Cards = Tyranno + Number 38 + Spright Elf /in GY: Petiteranodon and Miscellaneousaurus

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33379559

Oviraptor + Baby + Nunu Combo with the Borreload Savage (when I used the card)

This combo is a demonstration that you can play around hand traps on Normal Summon by first choosing to resolve Nunu to come and if Oviraptor is negated on Normal Summon at least you can King of the Feral Imps and continue having some move to perform.

 

*If instead of Nunu it was: Oviraptor + Baby + Nauya you would combo normally and if you were interrupted in the Normal Summon just do the combo that I show you next.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33335815

Nauya + any Monster = RANK-8 /in GY: 4 more important of the Ogdoadic names

This is good if for example you give Normal Summon Ovirapor and the opponent negates it to extend moves and pass with something that guarantees you to survive.

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33335402

Nunu + any Level4 Monster = I:P Masquerena + Aron, the Ogdoadic King

(at the time I used the Ogdoadic LV8 Aron but the idea behind it is the same)

 

Scrap Raptor = XYZ RANK-4 (Bagooska) or XYZ RANK-8 or Scrap Wyvern + Scrap Raptor (with 1 pop on the way without targeting)

Just so you know that Scrap Raptor itself can be an interrupt in many different ways like through a RANK-4 like Evilswarm Exciton Knight or Dingirsu, the Orcust of the Evening Star or Scrap Wyvern pop + Knightmare Unicorn

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-33336243

Snake Rain + Discard = I:P Masquerena + Aron, the Ogdoadic King

(at the time I used the Ogdoadic LV8 Aron but the idea behind it is the same)

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46461541

Snake Rain + Discard + any Level4 Monster = I:P Masquerena + Bagooska

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46461795

Snake Rain + Discard + Oviraptor = I:P Masquerena + Tyranno + Linkuriboh /in Hand: Water Lily /in GY: Miscellaneousaurus

First: Archosaur add Double Evolution Pill and make Linkuriboh + I:P Masquerena

 

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46462298

Lost World + Oviraptor + Keurse = Tyranno + Abyss Dweller + Number 38 /Access to all 4 Ogdoadic Names and Miscellaneousaurus in GY

 

or

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=813757-46462132

Oviraptor + Baby + Aleirtt = Tyranno + Dolkka + Number 38 /in Hand: Water Lily /Access to 3 Ogdoadic Names and Miscellaneousaurus in GY

 

What do you do if you draw one of the bricks(Keurse or Aleirtt)? Simple, do the combo normally and at the end of the Knightmare Unicorn and use the eff to shuffle himself back to the extra deck and that way you can discard the Brick to the GY.

This was a move that Adamancipator with Block Dragon did a lot, but in their case it wasn't to take a Brick from the deck, but to open space on the field to give summons from Block Dragon.

deck_description:
Updated version, with new combo that makes onomat engine much stronger than before because it can withstand negates in the process.

Why 6 onomat monsters? - No, i have in total 10 onomat monsters and 1 pot of prosperity (not counting onomatopaira). 

Important: Onomatopaira + Onomatopickup or similar 2 card combos that can lead you to get the 3 unique onomat monsters in hand, after you normal summon Utopic Onomatopoeia i recommend always to use the effect of Bancho first to special summon itself from hand and after that use the effect of Utopic Onomatopoeia, in that way your opponent will wait and target zs utopic sage or utopia double for negate and even if he use negate u can still make a good board.

Important: If you have the 3 unique onomat monsters in hand and you proceed with the strategy above, i recommend to summon utopia double using Dododowarf and Utopic Onomatopoeia as materials, use eff and summon Leo Utopia Ray, if utopia double is negated then summon Utopic Future Slash on top and use eff to detach the other onomat monster that are in his materials in gy. After use the eff of Bancho to revive Utopic Onomatopoeia and use the eff of Dododowarf from gy. Summon Zs Utopic Sage and use eff to summon ascended sage, overlaw Bancho and ascended for utopia - c39 - Dragonar etc ...

 

Note: Zs utopic sage is high risk because it's target for negate, so use it in powerful combos that can make a good board even if he is negated.

 

Most used 2 card combos in the deck:

Onomat spell + Ascended sage 

Onomat spell + Onomat monster

Onomatopaira + Onomatopickup

Onomat Spell + Armed

Note: Zexal Construct, reinforcement and pot of prosperity are included too.

 

Astraltopia can make board alone or be extender and used in combos but i play him x2 coppies because he is not that powerful, it's just little boost for the deck.

Kuriboh is mainly used just to strenghten Astraltopia and increase the number of the cards that can work with astraltopia and generally to boost the deck. 

If some of you like xyz change tactic, that's fine, you can choose between numbers protection or xyz change tactic.

In my previous uploads i had Dragonic ray but i removed him because he can be played probably once in 20 duels and only if utopia double is negated in combo with Armed sage.

Note: Ascended/Armed sage with utopia double trigger chain link that can make cards such as veiller useless. 

Utopic slash + downerd magician is used for zeus with 6 materials, that's powerful. Also, if u need follow up, on top of dragonar (no material) u can summon utopic slash for zeus too.

For budget version just remove droplet and number 90, target for replacement lightning storm, evenly matched etc...

For master duel instead number 90 u can play Rhongo.

I am lazy to write more...

Ahhh... At last, with Icejade Aegirine Rahn's release, my favourite deck is now finally playable.

The deck's really simple, your playstyle will depend on your starting hand. We have 2 playstyles: 


- Icejade Kosmochlor + Icejade Curse  lock. You'll need 3 cards in order to set up that lock, the 2 cards mentionned before as well as our field spell. This lock makes it so that your opponent is unable to activate the effects of monsters on the field and with a 3000 defense body + the field spell's attack reduction, getting out of that lock is pretty tough. The pretty neat thing about that combo is that it doesn't even require a normal summon and you'll be able to go into other combos depending on how good your starting hand is. You usually wanna go for this combo whenever you're able to since it's such a pain in the butt for the opponent to deal with.

- Synchro out whichever lvl 10 you prefer. This playstyle is a lot more straightforward and will be much more used than the previous one considering how easy it is to pull off. There are multiple ways of doing it depending on your starting hand. If you have 1 Deep Sea Diva , you'll be able to get a lvl 10 synchro out really easily. Normal summon her, special summon Guitar Gurnards Duonigis, use its effect to increase Diva's level and synchro them into the Deep Sea Prima Donna OR increase Guitar Gurnards Duonigis 's level and synchro into a level 8 monster. Use Prima Donna's effect to special summon Icejade Aegirine ( who you can use to search whatever you need ) and then synchro whichever lvl 10 synchro you prefer. I'll usually summon Icejade Gymir Aegirine since it's my favourite card but don't be like me, summon Baronne instead. You can also do this whole combo with just 1 Icejade Aegirine Rahn  and 1 Icejade card to dump without even using your normal summon.

Oh wait i forgot another combo; Marincess Coral Anemone into Worldsea Dragon Zealantis . It's pretty much just a board wipe against non-water decks since Coral Anemone locks you into water monsters, making it so that Zealantis can only summon back water monsters. Go for it if your opponent has a card that's somehow both untargettable and indestructible or if you just want to see them suffer as their monsters are all banished. 

That's pretty much it, I told you the deck was simple. If you're lucky enough, you could both pull off the lock AND get a lvl 10 synchro out! *sigh* It's a pretty fun deck to play, borderline rogue tier *inhales copium*. You'll be able to beat meta decks with a good enough starting hand. Overall, become a viable deck thanks to Aegirine Rahn so you should give it a try!

deck_excerpt: "In the deep space of the sea I have found my moon."
deck_description:
Do you enjoy fish? Anagrams? Nuke effects? And incredible artwork? Well, do I have the perfect archetype for you!

Ghoti are an archetype comprised of Fish type monsters that play during your opponent's turn by Synchro summoning and banishing their own cards  to bring forth their boss monster Ghoti of the Deep Beyond .

Main Deck:

Part 1: Monsters

Chapter 1: Residents of the Oceanic Cosmos (Ghoti)

It should be noted that all LV2 Ghoti's are Tuners, all of the besides Zep share the effect to "During the Standby Phase of the next turn after this card was banished: You can Special Summon this banished card. During your opponent's Main Phase, if this card was Special Summoned this turn, you can (Quick-Effect): Immediately after this effect resolves, Synchro Summon 1 Fish Synchro Monster using this card you control.".

  • Paces, Light of the Ghoti - One of the best tuners in deck! You can banish this card to summon another fish from hand, meaning you get to summon something else and put this guy in the banished zone to be brought back later.
  • Shif, Fairy of the Ghoti - Shif can banish itself from your GY boosting a fish you control while doing so, being a great target to be sent to the GY via Lifeless Leaffish or discarded by Icejade Aegirine Rahn .
  • Zep, Ruby of the Ghoti - Can banish itself from your hand to banish another fish from the GY. This card is different from the other tuners, it summons itself the moment its banished during your opponent's turn and when special summoned it immediately Synchros a fish, this card is the best target for Arionpos, Serpent of the Ghoti .
  • Ixeep, Omen of the Ghoti - This fella can special summon itself if you banished a fish, meaning next turn you can get Ariopos up so you can go into Askaan, the Bicorned Ghoti and then Ghoti of the Deep Beyond . This card is basically 2 extra searcheable copies of Minairuka .
  • Snopios, Shade of the Ghoti - The best card in the deck. Great level, allows you to get rid of dead ghotis in hand and grave so they can come back later, and can recycle itself from the banished zone by banishing a fish from grave, which can be a dead Askaan, the Bicorned Ghoti or Zep, Ruby of the Ghoti . It can also make a card on the field be banished instead of being sent to the GY, disabling cards like Bystial Druiswurm .

Part 2: Monsters

Chapter 2: Creatures of the Abyss (Fish)

  • Beautunaful Princess - Summons any of your small ghotis or Lifeless Leaffish from Deck.
  • Lifeless Leaffish - Gets Shif in grave works wonders under Dimension Shifter to banish your tuners, good level to make Serpent.
  • Abyss Shark - Makes Number 4: Stealth Kragen and searches either Silent Angler , your tuners, leafless, Minairuka or Ixeep letting you make White Aura Monoceros with the tuners or if you have another LV4 Bahamut Shark and then Toadally Awesome .
  • Silent Angler - Good extension.
  • Minairuka - The new PHHY world premier, Summons itself and banishes a face-up fish to negate a card until the end of your opponent's turn, its summon being a quick-effect means you can get materials on board if you dont have enough materials for a synchro during your opponent's turn.
  • Icejade Aegirine Rahn - Makes Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying which benefits from your banishing or Icejade Gymir Aegirine who can protect your cards and comes back if your opponent has their cards banished, which you can trigger with your ghotis.

Part 2: Spells

Chapter 1: Waves of Stardust (Field Spell)

  • The Most Distant, Deepest Depths - Banishes a fish from hand to add a Ghoti. Sets up your ghotis in the banished zone, adds new monsters to hand, has a way to recycle itself.

Part 3: Extra Deck

Chapter 1: Cosmos 

  • Arionpos, Serpent of the Ghoti - Banishes a Ghoti upon its summon which can be Zep, Ruby of the Ghoti to tune it right away, if this card is used for a synchro summon you can banish a fish in grave to add a monster with equal or lower level, allowing you to get tuners, Ixeep or Minairuka for extension or Snopios to set your next turn and more. 
  • Askaan, the Bicorned Ghoti - Banishes a fish and a card your opponent controls, if this card is banished you can banish a fish to summon this guy back, if you have a dead zep this makes Deep beyond, its a nice interruption with set-up.
  • White Aura Whale - Lightning storm on fins? Big body and can attack twice with piercing. If this card gets destroyed you can summon it back by banishing fish which is nice.
  • Ghoti of the Deep Beyond - Big nuke, big booty, you summon this guy when your opponent cannot extend or do more plays so you can swing for game when you re-summon it back.

Final Thoughts: Fun deck, lacks more good fish Ed monsters, has big problems with its playstyle, by playing in the opponent's turn it means they have a chance to draw a handtrap or just DRNM you, Drnm needs you to run Alpha because if you cant make your synchros you wont be living for another turn. Its a fine casual deck that likes the generic water support having a interesting playstyle with some of the best artwork in the modern era. 10/10 would synchro summon again.

card and effects

copernicus; he mills a card to thegy, usually used to link gilgamesh and then you pend him back to make the rank 4 ceaser

kepler: searches you a Dark contract and concidered your second starter

gryphon: specials from the hand if you have another D/D, what you will usually use to summon gilgamesh

swirl slime: he can fuse from the hand but usually milled since he specials a D/D from ur hand

necro slime: copernicus target, fuses from the grave by banishing it and another monster, usually summons small genghis

lamia, the second mill target, discard or destroy a D/D or contract card from the hand or field to special itself, copernicus target if you dont have gryphon or kepler

cerberus: the monster effect is bad but his pend effect makes a monster you control become lvl 4 and gains 400 afk, used on kepler when it pended back with gryphon

orthros: pend going first you can pop a monster you control and a spell on the field, usually itself if you have another low scale in hand

Berfomet: when specialed he can chanhe his level, i usually use him with highhowl for synchro plays

nighthowl: when NORMAL SUMMONED revives a D/D, kind of a tech option on turn 3 to summon big alexander which should have 6k atk by that point in the duel

Ghost: when sent to the gy you can target a DD in ur gy and send another copy to the gy, when banished can return banished DD to the gy, usually used with little ghengis to make siegfried

Thomas: pend:can return a D/D face up in ED to the hand, good for getting back stuff like kepler monster: can destroy a pend in the scale to summon another lvl8, usually vice king typhon

vice king typhon: your garnet, you usually want to use it with thomas effect as fodder, if used to summon an ED card that monster gets the effect to pop a card then recycle a dark contract and gain 1k lp

Oblivion king abyss ragnarok: when summoned he can revive a guy, as a scale you can revive another DD but half the dmg ur opp takes this turn

Go! DDD rage king: as a pend he can stop 1 dark contract in the standby phase and if you have a lvl 5 or above D/D you dont need to tribute

Dark contract with the gate: ur searcher (note all contracts are continuous and you lose 1k every standby ohase)

withthe swamo king; you can fuse with card in ur hand, field and gy

patent license: if ur opp summons a monster with the same type as a D/D/D monster you control ur opp takes 1k lp and they cant summon that type for the rest of the turn (fusion synchro, xyz, and link)

With eternal darkness; if you have 2 D/D scales your monsters cant be destroyed, sent to gy, tributed, fused, synchrod, or linked bu ur opps effects

D/D headhunt: basically skystriker widow anchor

deck_name: Shaddolls Branded In Tears | December 2022 Banlist
deck_excerpt: Shaddolls Branded in Tears | December 2022 Banlist
deck_description:
RECYCLING THE DECK!

I've liked shaddolls since I got back into the game in 2020, in fact, you could they say they got me back in, so heaven on earth I will BRING THIS DECK TO THE META , NO MATTER HOW MUCH OF A FRANKENSTEIN CREATION I HAVE TO BUILD (within a reasonable budget) WITH IT!

Anyway, this is my current decklist so I'll explain.

7-8 Shaddolls Monsters are pretty reasonable number; Thouh 2 Shaddoll Hedgehogs & Squammata are due to a dark target for Branded Fusion and For a decent target for sending off Scherin. You can argue the Shaddoll Names you play, but they can be recycled and adjusted to your fitting.

The Dogmatika Package is quite good for setting up schism and getting a monster negation. The Incredible Ecclecia is there for just straight up lore, as well as its decent recovery and fusions interuption. As well as for any synchro and xyz plays, as it can special summon itself if your opponent controls a monster, though remove at your preference, if you want, add another nadir.

Scherin is Good for rank 4 xyz , you can make time thief redoer to fuse when you don't have other options. As well as, being able to send off of fusions spells for increased field prensce. Using other Tear names ends up sending your spells and such, so I feel running only 3 of Scherin to be a nice compromise

The Branded Fusion package is quite standard in any dark/light fusion build, as it allows for quite easy fusing on either turn. 3 Fusions , 2 Albazs is fine.

For the rest, you can customise your hand traps(and board breakers) to how you see fit, I'm too much of a "budget" player to spend for the bystials (except for Bystial Baldrake as it seems decent and cheap). Though, I would recomend having 1 light handtrap, for any fusing you do on your turn, and which you didn't draw in your starting hand.

For the Extra deck; 2 Apkhalone is decent, you send one off Nadir, and have one to use. You can also recycle it back with Scherin(if you dont banish it, but if you do , lubellion), 2 Construct, though this can be replaced with another winda if you want. For the Albaz fusions, you only really need 1 lubellion, as you can recycle back with scherin if needed, it can recycle itself back, and even if you can't , you should be able to attempt game with your remaing albion , after sending one. Titanclad is there for more Dogmatika synergy, but you can replace it with Gururua , as that is a more meta card, I just didn't want to buy it for its price. Gravity controller is there for the Shaddoll Fusions, remember , you can use any non-fusions after Branded Fusion OR any of the albaz fusions THAT FUSE.

The side again, can be customised to suit your tastes. I have Abyss Dweller in the Side and not main, due to not wanting to have other fusions, but you may feel that substituting it for the 2nd construct more to your liking. I wanted to also, make the deck TRAP SHADDOLLS, after the 1st game, in case of ANTI-SPELL and such, I also personally have a soft spot for the trap variant, as that was my first meta deck. I went 3 wins and 1 draw against Tear at locals with and adjusted version of this, mainly having sinister shadow games and paleozoic dinomiscus in the main, but I think changing them for handtraps&Board Breakers is probably better.

My Channel dosen't have any clips with Nadir yet, as I literally recieved the cards before locals, so I only have replays with the Non-Nadir Variant, though this can showcase some of what the deck can do.

This abyss actor deck includes all kinds of ways to disrupt and overtake your opponent. By using Abyss actor extras and placing curtain raiser, or by using dramatic story with liberty dramatist or sassy rookie, you can set up a rather powerful board. It shouldn't be very difficult to get an end board with a set opening ceremony (by either adding it to your hand or setting it off of abysstainment), the link 2 (without using the field spell effect), and a pendulum summoned monster. The key to remember is to set wild hope in your spell/trap zone with the link 1, then with the link 2 set Madona. Do NOT mix these two up. Also remember that your monsters archetype lock you, so it's best to wait for the following turn to try for an Xyz or Link play. It can be tricky to get the deck down, but I'm sure you'll all figure it out with enough practice. Board breakers in the side in the event your opponent is far too strong for a direct approach.
