This deck aims to catch your opponent off guard by going blind second. If you lose the dice roll and your opponent goes first, you're perfectly set up. If they go second then you still have the Floo engine to play from, with extra consistency cards like Terraforming, and the pots.

In game 2 if you think your opponent will go second or if you elect to go first, you can swap out the going second cards for D-barrier, Feather Storm, Anti-Spell, and Trap Trick.

I put D-Shifter in the side as it's a dead card vs Kashtira and the mirror match up, but is a valuable option should you face the new tear or other decks that require effects in the GY.

Tbh the extra deck is incredibly tight, and the side deck is just to be a placeholder for potential main deck tech's and not a real side deck. But the idea is that the deck plays like swordsoul, but uses the resonator/RDA engine to blow up the field. I feel like a lot of swordsoul decks tend to just be Tenyi Swordsoul, so this is my attempt at making something different - even if it doesn't perform as optimally as very good counterpart lol. I just want to be able to show some love to my favorite YGO monster :)

I also think you could probably play the deck more heavy on the Resonator/RDA side if you want; and it'd probably make that portion of the deck much more consistent since the SwoSo cards can really take off on their own. (In this iteration I'd probably have Mo Ye be the only SwoSo monster at 3; and add Chaos Mirage Dragon w/some other wyrm chaos monsters? Tbh if playing chaos then Bystials definitely have a spot as well in the deck).
This deck was made to merge an unplayable deck with a broken one.

deck_excerpt: "Be happy for this moment. This moment is your life."
deck_description:
Do ya'll remember Firekings? 

Manadome is the 4th archetype coming from the World Destruction series, focusing around destroying their own monsters and making big leveled Synchro monsters. 

Main Deck: 

Chapter 1: The Terrarium and its Keeper (Manadomes)

All Manadome are Lv2 Fairy Tuners that share the following effects:

  1. If you control "Visas Starfrost" or a monster with 1500 ATK/2100 DEF, you can Special Summon this card (from your Hand).
  2. If this card is Destroyed by battle or card effect: You can Special Summon 1 (Of itself) from your Deck.
  • Manadome Meek - The most important tuner in deck! When destroyed it summons another one of itself from your deck and you can increase its level by 2! Giving you access to level 6 synchros like Coral Dragon or Stardust Charge Warrior or if you made it a level 4 you can go into Adamancipator Risen - Dragite , Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon to go into Bystial Dis Pater , Draco Berserker of the Tenyi and more. You want to get these guys on the field ASAP!
  • Manadome Hearless - Unlike Meek its effect upon summon is giving a boost to all synchro monsters on field. Its mostly used to climb or to be blown up, but still important enough to be ran at 3.
  • Manadome Riumheart - Like the other heart counterparts (helps their specific gimmick and adds a monster) Rium is a 3 of, being able to special summon himself from your hand destroying a "Manadome" or "Heart" monster you control and adding a manadome card from your deck to your hand. His effect is also very important to trigger their field-spell which I will talk about later.
  • Visas Starfrost - Visas finally found his home in this archetype! His effect to blow up cards is important to trigger your tunners, being a LV6 tuner means him with Manadome Riumheart or Scareclaw Reichheart means you get a LV10 synchro on board like Baronne de Fleur , and its an important card since he is used as a material to link into Scareclaw Light-Heart or to fusion summon Vicious Astroud which can help you extend into another synchros or swing for game. Manadome Abscission GY effect helps you summon him in case you dont have things you want to destroy.

Chapter 2: Frightening Monsters: (Scareclaw and Bystial)

  • Scareclaw Reichheart and Scareclaw Light-Heart - Reich is here to be your 1500/2100 monster, and since he can special summon himself to the field... He will be searching Scareclaw Arrival which helps bringing him or visas back so you can tune them into big synchros (It should be noted Nova is not OPT). As for Scareclaw Light-Heart he can be made with Reich or Visas giving you access to Primitive Planet Reichphobia which is the field-spell you want to stay with for reasons I will get to later... It also adds Visas or Reich, so if you didnt special summon reich you can do it now.
  • Bystial Magnamhut , Bystial Baldrake , Bystial Druiswurm and Bystial Dis Pater - Your deck has a lot of Light/Dark monsters you wouldnt mind being banished, they also offer Lv6 bodies for your Meek or Hearless while giving removal with Druis and Interruption with Baldrake. As for the Big Daddy synchro here he can retrieve your banished Visas or Heart monsters used for Vicious Astroud 's fusion summoning , giving you extension and negation with its effects, you will be making him with Accel Synchro Stardust Dragon who's effect revives a Lv2 or lower tuner from GY.
  • Vicious Astroud - Astround is the first contact fusion from the GY, using Visas and another Heart, this LV8 fusion destroys a monster upon its summon and receives half of its ATK. Extension, gives uses for dead monsters, puts things in the banished zone for Dis Pater, with any other Manadome he makes a Lv10 synchro. Insane card design.

Chapter 3: Conflict (S/T)

  • Primal Planet Kalarium - Now remember what I said about you wanting Reichnophobia in the field zone ASAP? This is the reason. Kalarium like the other Visas planets can add him or a monster of its archetype, Kalarium can also revive one of your Manadome tuners that were destroyed by effect! Meaning you get a Lv4 and Lv2 if you destroy Meek! But remember how the tuners special summon themselves if you have a monster with 1500/2100 well... the spell happens to change their stats meaning you cant summon the tuners... Yeah, you want to revive something to then get rid of it.
  • Manadome Abscission - Destroy a monster, adds Kalarium or a Manadome S/T if you control the planet. Its GY effect allows you to summon Visas or any Heart from your hand.
  • Manadome Reframing - Generic negation if you control a Synchro and recycles your dead tuners, the last effect will be always live.

Chapter 4: Culmination (Synchros)

  • Stardust Charge Warrior - Stepping stone to your Lv10s or your Lv8s like Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon 
  • Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon ,Adamancipator Risen - Dragite , Baronne de Fleur and Bystial Dis Pater - Negate gang, make sure to have a Meek in grave so Dragite is alwasy live.
  • Chaos Angel , Draco Berserker of the Tenyi , Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying and Manadome Prime-Heart - Big beaters that Banish stuff.
  • Cross-Sheep - Works too damn well with Vicious Astroud 

Example of a Combo: 

See attached video.

Final Thoughts:

As usual the Visas storyline decks hit all the right spots, and unlike Tears this one isnt as broken and wont kill my family! They have a solid base of what they want to do and how they achieve it, all they need is another tuner and a better boss monster, I didnt even touch on Prime-Heart because of all Heart monsters he is the most Eh out of them. But this deck has a bright future ahead without having to fear Sprights seeing as Elf was found dead with 66 bullet wounds.

I only really played Tear for a few days before before the new banlist dropped, and not a ton of Branded either, don't expect anything good from me.

A few things I would consider are upping the amount of Polymerization in deck, since it isn't a dead draw and it let's you load your Graveyard with more King of the Swamp if you draw both it and Polymerization, or 2 King of the Swamp. I would also consider changing the number of the Hex-Sealed Fusions. I like playing 3 dark because you can then send it with Branded Fusion, or you can use a Tearlament name to do both a Lubellion summon and a Tear summon. It's also debatable whether you play Despia, Theater of the Branded, but to be completely honest I just like having an extra target off Aluber other than Fusion and Lost. Tragedy is debatable at 3, but I don't have an argument either way so you can make that decision on your own. I also know that plenty of Tear decks played Mudragon and Garura, but honestly I didn't know how to play Tear optimally at its peak, so that's a decision others can make for themselves if they decide to pick this up. I should probably run handtraps in the deck, but I frankly don't care enough right now. 

The Extra Deck is very debatable, I don't quite know just what you want to be playing in there, but I just picked what I thought might be good. Would recommend tinkering with it if you explore it further.

Any constructive criticism would be appreciated! <3

deck

So instead of biting the bullet and dropping money on bystials, decided to combine P.U.N.K with Swordsoul. The synergy is pretty decent as you can do some funny plays(mentioned below) and no one really expects someone to be playing P.U.N.K with Swordsoul. There definitely are some things that could be changed with this list:

1. Playing another Jam Drive; its a great extender and definitely would be better to have more than one in grind games where I only see P.U.N.K names. Although in testing it seemed that it was more common to see more Swordsoul names (due to P.U.N.K cards searching each other and thinning the deck), so the second baxia came in clutch. If I end up playing more P.U.N.K names, definitely this will be a must.

2. More level 7 maindeck monsters; definitely the deck could be a little more fun if kashtrias were mixed in, I tried using more tenyi names but in the end, they usually would just be bricks. Doing something like a Fenrir and then summoning a level 3 P.U.N.K card allowed me to get barrone out faster for nub protection.

3. Playing more P.U.N.K names; although the deck would be more consistent in P.U.N.K combos if more names where played (like another foxytune or a madame spider), I didn't want the deck to be mostly P.U.N.K as I wanted to make sure Swordsoul combos were more consistent.Also playing another field spell would also be good, but I kept bricking with it in testing.

Deck Strengths:

1. You can do a full P.U.N.K combo without normal summoning (emergency tele). This leaves the normal summon open for cards like Mo ye that let you extend into swordsoul combos.

2. You can make an amazing dragon with Chixao and Sharakusai, this means you can use jam drive to go into psychic end.

3. The Tenyis are level 7, so you could summon vishuda and use emergency teleport to quickly make a barone.

4.The typical end board is; Barone + Psychic End + Chixiao/final sigma (with a normal hand).  If you are able to draw the right mix of swordsoul names and P.U.N.K names (which is a lot easier than it seems due to ogre dance, foxytune, emergence, and pot of d), the end board is; Barone + Psychic End + Chixao + Sharakusai (lets you get into amazing dragon) + Gabu (searchable imperm).

Deck Weaknesses:

1. It's not good if you only draw into only P.U.N.K  because it usually means your going to thin most of your extenders (like jam drive). You can still put up a decent board (a tower or a Sharakusai + level 8). 

2. Unless you see emergency teleport, it usally means you can't get the optimal endboard unless you have the proper cards to search your P.U.N.K extenders.

3. The deck can die to nib, which means you usually want to try to make barone as soon as possible, none of the P.U.N.K cards (in main deck) have effects on summon, which means your opponent can nib you before you can resolve something like a ze amin.

Naturia Madolche (with post Feb 203 banlist Earth Fairy support):
Before the banlist it'd be really fun to play 60 cards with full powered Ishizu support, but after that the deck has to make changes to cope with the new meta (possibly Kashtira with Bystial still lying around)

- The Madolche support is excellent both early game and mid-to-late game. But now that Tearlaments get nerfed it's more helpful playing mid game so the core cards are a bit limited. Searchable using Seedlings

- Naturia is for going first, able to withstand a lot of handtraps and able to spam during opponents turn. 

- Dweller will become a lot weaker after the banlist.

- Rafflesia is really easy now to summon and gd's trap hole is for Nibiru (possibly the best counter to Madolche)

- Dark Ruler is for Swordsoul and many other full board control deck, comboing with Tiaramisu for wiping the board.

- Droll is so much better after the banlist so it's really helpful putting 3 in the side deck.

- Ash should only be played second so into the Side Deck

- Now that trap decks are much stronger it's always better to play Antjaw than Vein because it's level 2, going for barkion will completely destroy your opponent, whereas bamboo and vein are coounterparts for go first and second when facing spell deck such as runick or Pendulum respectively.

- Baronne de Fleur is also an option replacing Rafflesia or 106. 

- Update: With Ancient Fairy eing released there're much more option firing a Madolche 1 card combo with either Angelly or Peting without normal summoning

deck_name: Eldlich control to Mayakashi *BEST OF THREE ONLY
deck_description:
Easily my most involved and maleable deck list; The main idea is that this deck has two "core" presets and one is stored in the side deck while the other is main decked so you can turn the game on its head between to keep you opponent guessing. The cores in question are (you guessed it) Eldlich control and Mayakashi. The rest of the deck is built on a zombie synchro/control engine (so obviously its geared more toward Mayakashi) but the eldlich part is consistent enough that it will mess with your opponents head when you pull it out.

The Eldlich core is 15 cards:

1x eldlich, 1x samurai skull, 2x cursed eldland, 1x zombie world, 1x called by, 3x conquistador, 2x Huaquero, 3x eldlixir, and 1x necro dragon (extra deck)

Very basic eldlich play and you don't need to use the extra deck very much so I almost added dogmatika punishment to the list (maybe an idea for the future), but it gets the job done. Looking at the eldlich side ins and whats different from how this deck plays the mayakashi side ins, we add an extra eldlich to up his consistency without compromising the spell/trap ratio as well as running an extra samurai skull to balance discard power after removing yuki musume and also an extra zombie world to up the consistency of the zombie world/rivalry of warlords lock. Finally we side out a tengu and replace him with zombie necro dragon because you may need that extra beat stick power and its one of the few synchros we can still make under these circumstances.

The mayakashi core is everything in the side deck

Its just normal Mayakashi play: search Dakki as fast as possible and climb the latter, end on Yuki-Onna (link 4), Gashadokuro, Dakki, and then hopefully a copy of the trap or maybe even a zombie world/rivalry lock. For a more in depth explanation of how basic mayakashi is played, most other mayakashi deck profiles will have an answer for you

Finally, lets talk about the engine:

The engine can be divided into 3 main parts: generic zombie stuff, negate, and anti-brick

The negate is exactly what you think it is; Ash blossom, Ghost mourner (or whatever other zombie hand trap you want to run there), and mazera

The anti brick is eldlich, bolan, and arguably samurai skull. Eldlich will discard spells and traps so you don't brick, bolan (by far the best anti brick in the deck) will discard excess monsters so that you can get at least one or two blockers on the field, and sam skull can put something in the grave, wether that be eldlich, balerdroch, spectralsword, or (my personal favorites), necroworld banshee or glow up bloom. Off bloom you can get an eldlich, balerdroch, or bolan to hand and off banshee you get a zombie world on field, but keep in mind you've already used your normal summon on samurai skull.

The zombie world stuff is everything else I haven't talked about yet: a couple tuners, some grave special summon from mezuki, rivalry, and also fun trap removal.

This deck IS NOT EASY by any means, but if you practice and learn how the cards interact, and start to understand how combos flow together, you can outplay pretty much any deck (even Kashtira and Tear, I know because I've done it myself). This deck is hard but rewarding, and bricks are few and far between.

Happy dueling

-Ornge

deck_excerpt: Pretty much just the average Ghoti deck... with a few minor changes
deck_description:
Ok, so if you've been looking into ghoti it should be fairly obvious how most of this works, but for those who haven't been looking at generic fish support for one too many hours: I got you.

The basic combo goes: make arianpos (level 6 synchro), use its effect to banish shif (the one that has navi from zelda inside it). Next turn (the opponents turn) you can make Askaan (the level 8 synchro) with arianpos and shif. If you had a zepp (the red one) in grave you can banish it with arianpos and have it come back to make the deep beyond (the level 10 synchro) for a board clear, but that's highly unlikely. thats the basic combo in a nutshell.

Now to explain the rest of the cards in the deck:

Supay duskwalker special summons a supay from deck, which makes you a level 6 synchro (all without a normal summon mind you)

sniopsis is run at one pretty much only to (A) keep you from bricking and (B) banish a ton to power up the deep beyond

If you banish anything you get ixeep for free (who when banished can cycle a ghoti spell/trap away from banished). You can see why that's good

White stingray is an anti brick level 4 special summon in a deck that uses level 2 tuners to make level 6 synchros

if you have minairuka, it will be on the field by the end of the turn and it threatens negate

we're on 3 shifter 1 crow for hand traps because our bosses do a lot of the negating and removal

in terms of spell traps we're on ghoti stuff as well as some good one of's 

Time to talk about weird combos:

If it looks like you bricked chances are you drew one of two hands: duskwalker, minstrel, a ghoti tuner, another monster, and one rando, OR beautunaful princess and 4 randos. Fortunately for you, those are some of the best hands in the deck.

in the duskwalker hand you need to special duskwalker and the supay from deck (in defense), normal the ghoti tuner, discard deep sea minstrel and banish whatever monster you want from opponent (they'll get it back later so it doesn't matter). Go into deep sea prima donna using the ghot tuner and duskwalker and activate its effect to unbanish the minstrel target and special a beautunaful princess (DO NOT ACTIVATE IT'S EFFECT) from deck to go into the level 8 ghoti.

From Beautunaful Princess, go into buzzsaw shark, activate its effect targeting itself and special out either a stingray if you think you can bring it back to the field later or a leaffish if you don't and make bahamut shark. detach the stingray or leafish and go into toadally awesome. Keep in mind you are locked into xyz for the rest of your turn though.

I think that's everything from the main deck? Time for extra deck!

We're on two of every ghoti except the spear because it sucks.

bahamut shark and toadally awesome for that combo.

Prima donna for her combo.

brionac might be a good option specifically going second in a hand where you'll have like exactly leaffish left in hand

White aura whale is a faster board clear if you'd rather get that then a level 8 ghoti

the adamancipator

the icejade is there if you'd rather a negate then a board clear

the swordsoul is there because it works absurdly well as the equivalent of accescode in a link deck

thats about it, happy dueling

-ornge

deck_excerpt: Don't forget to check out the gameplay - Dragon Link, Grass, Pendulum
deck_description:
Pendulum Dragon Link - MD Season 14

Don't forget to check out the gameplay.

Shiranui is slow and clunky and I don't like that so I'm fixing it

this deck can go first or second (I recomend second). If you start with squiresaga, you pretty much win the game but otherwise you have to get a little crafty. From Squiresaga, you bring out spectralsword and make immortal dragon. what you do now depends on what you have in your hand:

if you have chiangshi in hand, activate immortal dragon, send gozuki, activate gozuki, banish squiresaga, special chiangshi, (activate squiresaga if you want, you don't have to) and then chiangshi send depends on whatever you have (for instance balerdroch is good if you have zombie world, while glow up bulb or eldlich are good for flooding the field, and sending mezuki to special spectralsword and using that and chiangshi to make shogunsaga is a gigachad play) but if you still end up with immortal dragon and chiangshi on board, make a shogunsaga activate it's effect to banish chiangshi and activate chiangshi's effect banishing immortal dragon to special summon it back. This lands you an almost guarunteed sunsaga next turn with two card destructions if shogunsaga gets destroyed during your opponents turn.

if you have zombie world and nothing else of use activate immortal dragon, send balerdroch, activate zombie world, and carnage ensues

if you have a masterful mayakashi shiranui saga activate immortal dragon, send mezuki to bring back squiresaga, make samuraisaga, set your trap and sit on that goofy little board

if you have rivalry send banshee, banish her to activate zombie world, and sit on the zombie lock

those are the basic ones but there's a bunch more to experiment with

if you do not start squiresaga, your options are a little more limited

samurai skul + a spell trap sends eldlich, activate eldlich in grave, ditch whatever spell trap, then summon eldlich 

bolan and anything creates a free blocker and a special summon during your opponents turn (if its chiangshi you likely get two off of that)

uni-zombie works approximately the same as sam skull 

For hand traps we're sitting on 3 mazera 3 ash blossom 

for spell/traps we're sitting on the zombie world/rivalry combo, as well as the mayakashi/shiranui summon lockout, the shiranui continuos which may let you escape bricking, and a quickplay that allows you to full combo going second

For extra deck I've already explained most of the shiranui monsters, so heres the rest of the explanation:

squiresaga is for weird situations where you start with a weird hand and you can make this and pretty much nothing else

wollow is the result of getting two chiangshi on board or chiangshi + uni-zombie + lvl 4. This actually comes up more than you would think

skillsaga supremacy is if you go too hard and you need some sychros back from banished

yuki onna does the same thing except from graveyard

vampire sucker also comes up once in a blue moon and because of the high frequency of big monsters in your deck if you have the resources turn 3 you can go into sucker and tribute summon for removal. She's a kaiju with like slightly harder summoning conditions

vampire fascinator is here because we can make her easily, and avendread savior is here because we can make him easily AND we can make him faster than a red eyes zombie necro

in terms of sides, we're on 3 shifter for if you ever get intoxicated and think that's a good idea, 1 nethersoul and 2 super poly for zombie world removal, 1 called by, 2 dark ruler, 1 absolute zero mayakashi because its hilarious if you ever get it to work, 3 cosmic cyclone, 1 sheridan because we can make hime, and 1 red-eyes zombie necro dragon because I ran out of ideas

happy dueling

-Ornge

deck_excerpt: Old Mathmech Board + 4 Counters Darkfluid Firewalldragon and Disabwurm
deck_description:
The Deck still works with the classic Mathmech Combo and you can get the same Endboard as constant as before. I discovered the new Cybersage Engine, which allows us, to add two big Interupptions to our Board.

 

You start the combo like the classic Mathmech combo with circular in Hand:

You send Sigma to thegrave, that specials circular, you special sigma with his effect and now you search:

1. The Trap (if u already have a spell in the Grave like cynet mining or small world, or if you got the mathmech equation in hand)

2. The Mathmech spell if you got no other spells in the grave

when you searched the right card, you xyz summon primathmech alembertian and search for diameter, normal summon him and special circular

after that you link summon the cyberse with with your two mathmechs (not the xyz)

If you already had a spelll in grave and searched the trap, you now use the effect of alembertian and special one of your mathmechs from the grave, now cyber wiutch activates and you banish the spell to get the ritual card and the cyber sage.

If u searched the Mathmech equation you dont activate the xyz and use the equation to special a mathmech in one of the cyber witchs zones and banish the equation from your grave to search the ritual cards

 

after you got the ritual cards in hand you use cyber witchs second effect to special one lvl 4 or lower cyberse from your grave and use it for the special summon of cyber sage, then u link the monster you special summopned to cyber witches zone and cyber with to get heatcode Talker

Then you draw one card and use the effect from cyber sage to summoon disabwurm with cyber witch in your grave and one other monster except your xyz

After that you use disabwurm and cyber sage to special summon the quantum dragon (synchro monster) and now you can take onee cyberse from your grave to your hand for a comeback next round.

now link all your monsters so you get the darkfluid firewalldragon with all 4 counters

deck_excerpt: "Hope is being able to see that there is light despite all of the darkness."
deck_description:
I was play-testing a Lightsworn deck at home (who's mechanics I discovered entirely on accident) when I realized to myself "Damn, this could be really good if used right!", so I made a more playable and fun version of this deck in this website!

Basically, the Lightsworn monsters kill themselves in order to give power to other Lightsworn monsters, specifically cards such as "Gragonith, the Lightsworn Dragon", and "Judgement Dragon". It's an archetype that's tricky to play, due to the fear of running out of cards in your deck (because trust me, it will happen fast if you're not careful), but if you manage to master this deck and use it to its ful potential, it can be a scary deck to fight against. 

One more thing to note about this deck is that although it can die fast, it also becomes seriously strong really fast as well. 

If you have anything you would like to say or recommend about this deck, please feel free to do so. :)

With the ban of Union Carrier, I think the Athena FTK is a lot less playable so if you still want to prevent your opponent from playing yugioh will have to rely on The World. If The World fails you can just build a negate board like any other normal combo deck.

deck_name: Traptrix / Post SD Beware of Traptrix
deck_excerpt: A pretty solid build in my opinion that could be insanely cheap if it wasn't for Prospy
deck_description:
Traptrix is an archetype that received some pretty impressive support, featured in the newest SD. Well I recommend buying the SD and thus I shall show ya all a potential build. Keep in mind that the deck has the potential to top a local. I shall proceed by explaining some of my choices.

1. Dimension Shifter: I'm pretty sure this guy won't see that much use after the bloodbath banlist and thanks to the fact that he helps Kashtira. Nevertheless keep in mind that Tears aren't entirely dead and they will pretty much be an engine now for other decks (including Kashtira). Apart from that, I consider shifter pretty strong versus most of decks that's why I choose not to drop him (although he could be dropped for sth like Ash)

2. Small number of Traptrix main deck monsters: Guys you really don't want to see a hand that contains much Traptrix names so it's probably better to keep their numbers low. However, I could maybe accept running one more copy of Dionea.

3. Dimensional Barrier: I firmly believe that Kashtira and possibly Branded are this new format's best decks. Dimensional Barrier is probably really effective against their respective strategies. Apart from that I consider the card effective versus all those Mikanko variants that popped out of nowhere as well as Purrely and the fan favourite Swordsoul strategies

4. Evenly Matched: I believe nobody has a say against Evenly's strength. Instead people will ask why it is main-decked. Well it's just another going 2nd strategy ('cause you won't always win the dice roll) and a fodder for Holetaea when going 1st (if you don't have access to Dionea SS recover a Trap hole)

That's it for this profile. I hope it helps you enough. As always I'm open to suggestions (especially since I'm in search for a budget alternative to Prosperity) and, any ideas and comments are welcome.
